### Pitfall 1: YAML quoting — parentheses break parsers silently

```
❌ Wrong — unquoted source with parentheses
source: Kernel v1 archive (profile: hermes-arquitectobi)

✅ Correct — quote the value
source: "Kernel v1 archive (profile: hermes-arquitectobi)"
```

Any `source:`, `description:`, or free-text field containing `()`, `[]`, `:`, `#` must be quoted. YAML parsers fail silently — the file appears valid but the field becomes garbled or the parser throws an error on that specific key. Always quote fields with special characters.

### Pitfall 2: Two files must be kept in sync when adding relation types

When adding a new relation type (e.g., `exposed_by`):
1. `cmdb/impact.py` — add to `DEPENDENCY_RELATIONS` (for traversal)
2. `cmdb/rules/relations.py` — add to `VALID_RELATION_TYPES` AND to `RELATION_TARGET_KINDS` (for validation)

Adding to only one file causes silent validation failures. The `cmdb_validate()` will return `valid=False` and the `errors` list will show "Unknown relation type."

